    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>What's Good for Persian Gulf Is Good for Brazil</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The criteria for what's in our ''national interest,'' so as to warrant an intrusive United States military presence, might be convincingly argued if a distinction could be found between having a U.S. naval presence in the Persian Gulf but no American presence in Brazil, which doesn't have the enforcement resources to stem man-made fires in the Brazilian rain forest (front page, Aug. 12).</p>
        <p>That nasty little war in the Persian Gulf has threatened worldwide oil supplies and delivery, which could be economically disruptive. The vast rain-forest fires in Brazil, which provide many settlers and farmers with their ''. . . only tool for transforming forest into farm or pasture,'' threaten the balance of nature and the very survival of the human species by exacerbating the greenhouse effect through the production of CO#2 byproduct and diminished forest capacity to remove greenhouse gases and produce oxygen.</p>
        <p>In law there is an instructive Latin phrase, a fortiori, which translates that if one fact is established, another fact included in it is all the more true.</p>
        <p>If it is true that the United States has a right to be in the Persian Gulf, which effectively involves only economics, then, a fortiori, the United States has not only a right, but a duty, to be in Brazil to prevent the fires that threaten human survival.</p>
        <p>I am not making an argument for such intervention; I am only sug-gesting that the subject be dis-cussed. ROBERT H. BLETCHMAN  Manchester, Conn., Aug. 12, 1988</p>
      </block>
